  "text": "Living within -or managing -an HIV epidemic necessarily involves a number of ongoing 'first' and 'second' order processes which influence the forms of emergence that become distinct characteristics of the virus-human-environment heuristic at particular historical moments. Some forms of emergence are novel -such as the change in condom use in recent years (Shisana et al., 2014, p. xxxii & 130) ; some are relatively short lived -such as the different government responses to the epidemic in South Africa [CITATION_1] and other forms of emergence are long term phenomena -such as non-adherence to medication in resource scarce settings (Gabillard, Lewden, Ndoye, Moh, Segeral, Tonwe-Gold, Etard, Pagnaroat, Fournier-Nicolle, Eholie, Konate, Minga, Mpoudi-Ngole, Koulla-Shiro, Zannou, Anglaret, Laurent, & Group, 2013) .",
